SIMPLE: wardrobe
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Wardrobe
<hw>Ward"robe`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>warderobe</ets>, OF. <ets>warderobe</ets>, F. <ets>garderobe</ets>;
of German origin. See <er>Ward</er>, <pos>v. t.</pos>, and
<er>Robe</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>A room or apartment where clothes are kept, or
wearing apparel is stored; a portable closet for hanging up
clothes.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Wearing apparel, in general; articles of dress or
personal decoration.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Flowers that their gay <qex>wardrobe</qex> wear.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>With a pair of saddlebags containing his <qex>wardrobe</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>T. Hughes.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A privy.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Wardroom</ent>⟦br⟧
